"Schulte P.M., Healy T.M., Fangue N.A.","Thermal performance curves, phenotypic plasticity, and the time scales of temperature exposure",2011,"Integrative and Comparative Biology","51","5",,"691","702",,,10.1093/icb/icr097,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80054887639&partnerID=40&md5=f9c445401239b1cab34e6722bbd67187","Department of Zoology, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada; Department of Wildlife, Fish and Conservation Biology, University of California at Davis, Davis, CA, United States","Schulte, P.M., Department of Zoology, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada; Healy, T.M., Department of Zoology, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada; Fangue, N.A., Department of Wildlife, Fish and Conservation Biology, University of California at Davis, Davis, CA, United States","Thermal performance curves (TPCs) describe the effects of temperature on biological rate processes. Here, we use examples from our work on common killifish (Fundulus heteroclitus) to illustrate some important conceptual issues relating to TPCs in the context of using these curves to predict the responses of organisms to climate change. Phenotypic plasticity has the capacity to alter the shape and position of the TPCs for acute exposures, but these changes can be obscured when rate processes are measured only following chronic exposures. For example, the acute TPC for mitochondrial respiration in killifish is exponential in shape, but this shape changes with acclimation. If respiration rate is measured only at the acclimation temperature, the TPC is linear, concealing the underlying mechanistic complexity at an acute time scale. These issues are particularly problematic when attempting to use TPCs to predict the responses of organisms to temperature change in natural environments. Many TPCs are generated using laboratory exposures to constant temperatures, but temperature fluctuates in the natural environment, and the mechanisms influencing performance at acute and chronic time scales, and the responses of the performance traits at these time scales may be quite different. Unfortunately, our current understanding of the mechanisms underlying the responses of organisms to temperature change is incomplete, particularly with respect to integrating from processes occurring at the level of single proteins up to whole-organism functions across different time scales, which is a challenge for the development of strongly grounded mechanistic models of responses to global climate change. © The Author 2011. Published by Oxford University Press on behalf of the Society for Integrative and Comparative Biology. All rights reserved.",,"acclimatization; animal; article; cell respiration; climate change; Cyprinodontiformes; environment; evolution; metabolism; mitochondrion; oxygen consumption; phenotype; physiology; temperature; thermodynamics; time; Acclimatization; Animals; Biological Evolution; Cell Respiration; Climate Change; Environment; Fundulidae; Mitochondria; Oxygen Consumption; Phenotype; Temperature; Thermodynamics; Time Factors; Cyprinodontoidei; Fundulus heteroclitus",,,,,,"Agrawal, A.A., Ecology: Phenotypic plasticity in the interactions and evolution of species (2001) Science, 294 (5541), pp. 321-326. , DOI 10.1126/science.1060701; Angert, A.L., Sheth, S.N., Paul, J.R., Incorporating population-level variation in thermal performance into predictions of geographic range shifts (2011) Integr Comp Biol, 51, pp. 733-750; Angilletta, M.J., (2009) Thermal Adaptation: A Theoretical and Empirical Synthesis, , Oxford, England: Oxford University Press; Angilletta, M.J., Huey, R.B., Frazier, M.R., Thermodynamic effects on organismal performance: Is hotter better? (2010) Physiol Biochem Zool, 83, pp. 197-206; Angilletta Jr., M.J., Niewiarowski, P.H., Navas, C.A., The evolution of thermal physiology in ectotherms (2002) Journal of Thermal Biology, 27 (4), pp. 249-268. , DOI 10.1016/S0306-4565(01)00094-8, PII 